39 46-10-3.
40 (a) There is created the Office of the Consumers' Utility Counsel, which shall be assigned
41 for administrative purposes only to the Department of Law. There is created the position
42 of director of the office. The director shall be appointed and removed by a committee
43 consisting of five members as follows, none of whom shall be employed by or be an officer
44 of any utility while serving on the committee:
45 (1) One member shall be a member of the House of Representatives appointed by the
46 majority leader of the House of Representatives;
47 (2) One member shall be a member of the House of Representatives appointed by the
48 minority leader of the House of Representatives;
49 (3) One member shall be a member of the Senate appointed by the majority leader of the
50 Senate;
51 (4) One member shall be a member of the Senate appointed by the minority leader of the
52 Senate; and
53 (5) One member shall be appointed by the Governor.
54 (b) The director shall be a practicing attorney qualified by knowledge and experience to
55 practice in public utility proceedings. The director shall receive compensation in an
56 amount equal to the annual salary set for each district attorney in paragraph (21) of Code
57 Section 45-7-4. In addition to such compensation, the director shall also receive
58 reimbursement for his or her reasonable and necessary expenses incurred in the
59 performance of his or her duties, as provided by law for state employees. The director shall
60 not engage in the private practice of law while employed as director. The director shall,
61 by December 31 of each year, submit a written report of the annual activities and
62 expenditures of the office to the Governor, the Speaker of the House of Representatives,
63 the President of the Senate, the chairperson of the House Committee on Energy, Utilities,
64 and Telecommunications, and the chairperson of the Senate Regulated Industries and
65 Utilities Committee.
